<subSubSection id="94A154849A0F434FFF57C9AAFDEA348E" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="1248" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246" type="description">
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A0F4349FF57C9AAFC6334B9" blockId="11.[178,1085,1214,1266]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246">E t y m o l o g y: The specific epithet (Latin, adjective: southern) alludes to the fact that this species currently represents the southernmost record of the genus.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A0F4349FF57C814FE7F3527" blockId="11.[178,1086,1281,1391]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246">D e s c r i p t i o n: Measurements (mm) and ratios (range): HL: 1.98-2.14; HW: 1.71- 1.83; PW: 1.89-2.10; PL: 2.38-2.64; EL: 1.28-1.49; TiL: 1.86-2.01; TaL: 1.43-1.53; TL: 13.4-15.1; HL/HW: 1.16-1.17; HW/PW: 0.87-0.90; PL/PW: 1.25-1.27; EL/PL: 0.54- 0.58; TaL/TiL: 0.75-0.77.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A0F4349FF57C86BFC9E35A4" blockId="11.[178,1085,1406,1516]" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246">
Large species (see measurements). Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A0F4349FD52C86BFCC235DB" box="[695,772,1406,1428]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
. Coloration: body black, with the apex of the abdomen (segments IX-X; posterior portion of segment VIII) brown to dark-brown; legs with blackish-brown femora and reddish-brown tibiae and tarsi; antennae blackish-brown; maxillary palpi reddish-brown to dark-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A0F434EFF57C8EEFE5631E8" blockId="11.[178,1085,1531,1582]" lastBlockId="12.[178,1085,219,416]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="1247" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246">
Head (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A0F4349FF10C8EEFEF93659" box="[245,319,1531,1553]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="1246">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) conspicuously oblong (see ratio HL/HW), with subparallel lateral margins (dorsal view), and distinctly narrower than pronotum (see ratio HW/PW); anterior pair of frontal punctures distinct; dorsal surface in posterior half and in lateral portions with double punctation, i.e., with irregularly spaced coarse macropunctures and with moderately dense micropunctation; micropunctures present also, though more sparsely, in anterior half of dorsal surface; interstices with distinct fine microreticulation composed of short transverse meshes anteriorly and transverse striae posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFC40CC45FC33312E" box="[933,1013,336,358]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Eyes (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFF5FCC78FECF31CB" box="[186,265,365,387]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) small and weakly convex, approximately one-fourth as long as postocular region in dorsal view.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57CCA5FC283273" blockId="12.[178,1085,432,571]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFEC2CCA5FEB2318E" box="[295,372,432,454]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) distinctly oblong (see ratio PL/PW); discal punctation pattern distinctive: 1+2 discal punctures situated laterally, i.e., about halfway between middle of pronotum and lateral margin; posterior puncture situated practically in posterior angle, separated from margin by a distance of approximately its diameter (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFC87CF12FC6B3255" box="[866,941,519,541]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
); surface with fine and distinct microreticulation composed of short transverse meshes (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFC73CF30FC243273" box="[918,994,549,571]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57CF5FFECC32F0" blockId="12.[178,1085,586,696]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFF1ACF5FFE8C3228" box="[255,330,586,608]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
) short, little more than half as long as pronotum (see ratio EL/PL); punctures (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFF17CF72FEFA3235" box="[242,316,615,637]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) moderately dense, large, but very shallow; interstices with distinct irregular microsculpture (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFE9ACF90FE0A32D3" box="[383,460,645,667]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
) rendering the surface nearly matt. Hind wings completely reduced.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57CFD2FCD43350" blockId="12.[178,1085,711,792]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Abdomen approximately as broad as elytra; punctation shallow, moderately dense on tergites III-VI, sparse on tergites VII-VIII; interstices with fine transverse microsculpture; posterior margin of tergite VII without palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57CE32FC63340C" blockId="12.[178,1085,807,1092]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">
3: protarsomeres I-IV strongly dilated (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFDBBCE32FD6A3375" box="[606,684,807,829]" captionStart="Figs 11-18" captionStartId="10.[178,218,1502,1524]" captionTargetBox="[181,1085,212,1492]" captionTargetId="figure-91@10.[178,1085,212,1497]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figs 11-18: Othius auster nov.sp.: (11) habitus; (12) head; (13) median portion of head; (14) pronotum; (15) postero-lateral portion of pronotum; (16) median portion of pronotum; (17) elytra; (18) postero-sutural portion of left elytron. Scale bars: 11-12, 14-15, 17: 1.0 mm; 13, 18: 0.5 mm; 16: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415941" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415941/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); sternites V-VII unmodified; sternite VIII posteriorly shallowly impressed, posterior margin weakly concave; posterior processes of hemitergites IX apically acute, but without tooth-like processes, barely reaching posterior margin of tergite X; sternite IX (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFD46CE6AFD3633DD" box="[675,752,895,917]" captionStart="Figs 19-22" captionStartId="11.[178,218,855,877]" captionTargetBox="[184,1076,212,836]" captionTargetId="figure-356@11.[178,1085,212,848]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 19-22: Othius auster nov.sp.: (19) male sternite IX; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (22) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 19-21: 1.0 mm; 22: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415943/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) broad, anteriorly deeply bifid, posterior margin deeply excised, aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFD6DCE89FD3A33FA" box="[648,764,924,946]" captionStart="Figs 19-22" captionStartId="11.[178,218,855,877]" captionTargetBox="[184,1076,212,836]" captionTargetId="figure-356@11.[178,1085,212,848]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 19-22: Othius auster nov.sp.: (19) male sternite IX; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (22) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 19-21: 1.0 mm; 22: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415943/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Figs 20-21</figureCitation>
) 1.8-2.0 mm long; parameres apically weakly dilated, far from reaching apex of median lobe, each with 4 apical setae; internal sac with 6 sclerotized internal structures (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFD56CEC2FCC633A5" box="[691,768,983,1005]" captionStart="Figs 19-22" captionStartId="11.[178,218,855,877]" captionTargetBox="[184,1076,212,836]" captionTargetId="figure-356@11.[178,1085,212,848]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 19-22: Othius auster nov.sp.: (19) male sternite IX; (20-21) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view; (22) internal structures of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 19-21: 1.0 mm; 22: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415943/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
): a long (
<quantity id="1B43AAEA9A08434EFC87CEC2FC7433A4" box="[866,946,983,1004]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
) and apically acute median basal structure, a shorter (
<quantity id="1B43AAEA9A08434EFDB4CEE1FD763441" box="[593,688,1012,1033]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" unit="mm" value="0.33">0.33 mm</quantity>
) median apical structure with a hookshaped apex (pointing ventrad), and two pairs of slender and straight lateral structures (length: approximately 
<quantity id="1B43AAEA9A08434EFE45C93AFE37340C" box="[416,497,1071,1092]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
), the inner pair apically obliquely truncate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57C94CFEFC3422" blockId="12.[178,1086,1108,1343]" box="[178,314,1108,1134]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">
<specimenCount id="CABDCC869A08434EFF57C94CFF013426" box="[178,199,1113,1134]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57C96CFC5F3576" blockId="12.[178,1086,1108,1343]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: This distinctive species is characterized not only by the morphology of the median lobe (particularly the internal structures), but also by the combination of large body size, a strongly oblong head, double punctation of the head, the characteristic microsculpture and punctation of the elytra, reduced hind wings, and the absence of a palisade fringe at the posterior margin of tergite VII. It additionally differs from the geographically closest congener, 
<taxonomicName id="1BBB7C8C9A08434EFD30C819FC883568" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="1999" box="[725,846,1291,1313]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lubricus">
<emphasis id="EECFDB1D9A08434EFD30C819FC883568" box="[725,846,1291,1313]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">O. lubricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by the more oblong pronotum and the much deeper posterior excision of the male sternite IX.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC04070F9A08434EFF57C843FD5F35B6" blockId="12.[178,1091,1366,1534]" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d b i o n o m i c s: Thetypelocalityissituatedatapass 
<quantity id="1B43AAEA9A08434EFBD2C843FF1435C1" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" unit="km" value="8.0">8 km</quantity>
to the northwest of Sa Pa. The discovery of 
<taxonomicName id="1BBB7C8C9A08434EFD42C861FCC035C1" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2015" box="[679,774,1396,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="auster">
<emphasis id="EECFDB1D9A08434EFD42C861FCC035C1" box="[679,774,1396,1417]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">O. auster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is remarkable in that it represents the first record from 
<collectingCountry id="A4AC479F9A08434EFE35C885FDEC35EE" box="[464,554,1424,1446]" name="Vietnam" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, the first record from the Oriental region, and the southernmost record of the genus as a whole (
<figureCitation id="44801B8A9A08434EFD61C8BBFD01358C" box="[644,711,1454,1476]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="2.[178,223,1223,1244]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,1212]" captionTargetId="figure-191@2.[178,1085,212,1212]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Map 1: Distribution of Othius in the East Palaearctic region east of the Himalaya, based on examined records (all records pooled). White circle: type locality of Othius auster nov.sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5415929" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5415929/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Map 1</figureCitation>
). The previous record in this respect was held by 
<taxonomicName id="1BBB7C8C9A08434EFED0C8DEFDB635A8" authority="ASSING, 1999" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="1999" box="[309,624,1483,1505]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Othius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="smetanai">
<emphasis id="EECFDB1D9A08434EFED0C8DEFE1D35A9" box="[309,475,1483,1505]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Othius smetanai</emphasis>
ASSING, 1999
</taxonomicName>
from Peitawushan in 
<collectingRegion id="1E7FC9ED9A08434EFCB7C8DEFC3535A9" box="[850,1011,1483,1505]" country="Taiwan" name="Pingtung" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Pingtung Hsien</collectingRegion>
, southern 
<collectingCountry id="A4AC479F9A08434EFF3CC8FDFEE335B6" box="[217,293,1512,1534]" name="Taiwan" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(approximately 
<geoCoordinate id="B98F61C89A08434EFE29C8FCFDE735B6" box="[460,545,1513,1534]" degrees="22" direction="north" minutes="37" orientation="latitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" precision="925" value="22.616667">22°37'N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="B98F61C89A08434EFDC9C8FDFD4B35B6" box="[556,653,1512,1534]" degrees="120" direction="east" minutes="46" orientation="longitude" pageId="12" pageNumber="1247" precision="925" value="120.76667">120°46'E</geoCoordinate>
).
</paragraph>
